# SpawnDev.ILGPU Project Conventions

## Project Structure

- **SpawnDev.ILGPU** is a fork/extension of ILGPU that adds browser-based GPU backends (WebGPU, WebGL) alongside the existing CUDA and OpenCL backends.
- The **ILGPU** project (the fork) is included directly in this workspace. We can and do modify ILGPU internals as needed (e.g. changing `internal` to `public`, adding intrinsics, fixing bugs). This is intentional — the fork exists specifically so we can make these changes.
- Do not hesitate to modify ILGPU source when that is the correct fix. Prefer clean modifications over awkward workarounds in SpawnDev.ILGPU.

## Code Quality Standards

- **No quick/temporary fixes.** Every change must be well thought out, high quality, and designed for the long term.
- **Cover edge cases.** This library transpiles .NET IL to CUDA, OpenCL, WGSL, GLSL, and WebAssembly. Developers write complex GPU kernels that must work reliably across all backends without bugs.
- **High performance.** The library enables efficient GPGPU across platforms. Performance-sensitive code paths must be carefully considered.
- **Plan before implementing.** For complex or multi-step fixes, switch to planning mode first to think through the approach. Don't rush into code changes.
- **Understand the full impact.** Before changing shared code (especially in ILGPU/), consider how the change affects all backends, not just the one currently being debugged.

## Testing

- Test all features as thoroughly as possible.
- When adding support for a feature or type (e.g. Half/f16), add tests for all value types the feature supports (float, int, double, long, Half, etc.).
- Never skip or disable tests unless there is absolutely no reliable way to make them work. Prefer fixing the root cause.
- The demo project contains unit tests (`BackendTestBase.Tests*.cs`) that run across all backends — use these to verify cross-backend correctness.

## WebGPU-Specific Reminders

- WebGPU requires 4-byte alignment for: buffer sizes, `writeBuffer` byte counts, `copyBufferToBuffer` sizes, and **bind group entry `Size` fields**.
- Use `WebGPUAlignment.AlignTo4()` consistently for all WebGPU buffer operations.
- When `LengthInBytes` returns a logical size, remember the actual GPU buffer may have been allocated with padded/aligned size.
- The `shader-f16` feature must be detected and `enable f16;` emitted in WGSL for native Half support.
